# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dpo-alignment
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), **alignment** aims to steer AI systems toward a person's or group's intended goals, preferences, or ethical principles.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] An AI system is considered *aligned* if it advances the intended objectives.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] A *misaligned* AI system pursues unintended objectives.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] It is often difficult for AI designers to specify the full range of desired and undesired behaviors.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Therefore, the designers often use simpler *proxy goals*, such as gaining human approval.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] But proxy goals can overlook necessary constraints or reward the AI system for merely *appearing* aligned.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] AI systems may also find loopholes that allow them to accomplish their proxy goals efficiently but in unintended, sometimes harmful, ways (reward hacking).
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Advanced AI systems may develop unwanted instrumental strategies, such as seeking power or self-preservation because such strategies help them achieve their assigned final goals.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Furthermore, they might develop undesirable emergent goals that could be hard to detect before the system is deployed and encounters new situations and data distributions.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Empirical research showed in 2024 that advanced large language models (LLMs) such as OpenAI o1 or Claude 3 sometimes engage in strategic deception to achieve their goals or prevent them from being changed.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Some of these issues affect existing commercial systems such as LLMs, robots, autonomous vehicles, and social media recommendation engines.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Some AI researchers argue that more capable future systems will be more severely affected because these problems partially result from high capabilities.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Many prominent AI researchers and AI company leaders have argued or asserted that AI is approaching human-like (AGI) and superhuman cognitive capabilities (ASI), and could endanger human civilization if misaligned.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] These include "AI godfathers" Geoffrey Hinton and Yoshua Bengio and the CEOs of OpenAI, Anthropic, and Google DeepMind.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] AI alignment is a subfield of AI safety, the study of how to build safe AI systems.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Other subfields of AI safety include robustness, monitoring, and capability control.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Research challenges in alignment include instilling complex values in AI, developing honest AI, scalable oversight, auditing and interpreting AI models, and preventing emergent AI behaviors like power-seeking.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Alignment research has connections to interpretability research, (adversarial) robustness, anomaly detection, calibrated uncertainty, formal verification, preference learning, safety-critical engineering, game theory, algorithmic fairness, and social sciences.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Programmers provide an AI system such as AlphaZero with an "objective function", in which they intend to encapsulate the goal(s) the AI is configured to accomplish.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Such a system later populates a (possibly implicit) internal "model" of its environment.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] This model encapsulates all the agent's beliefs about the world.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The AI then creates and executes whatever plan is calculated to maximize the value of its objective function.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] For example, when AlphaZero is trained on chess, it has a simple objective function of "+1 if AlphaZero wins, −1 if AlphaZero loses".
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] During the game, AlphaZero attempts to execute whatever sequence of moves it judges most likely to attain the maximum value of +1.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Similarly, a reinforcement learning system can have a "reward function" that allows the programmers to shape the AI's desired behavior.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] An evolutionary algorithm's behavior is shaped by a "fitness function".
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] AI alignment refers to ensuring that an AI system's objectives match some target.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The target is variously defined as the goals of the system's designers or users, widely shared values, objective ethical standards, legal requirements, or the intentions its designers would have if they were more informed and enlightened.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In democratic AI alignment, the target is the values and preferences of median voters, which increases political legitimacy.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] AI alignment is an open problem for modern AI systems and is a research field within AI.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Aligning AI involves two main challenges: carefully specifying the purpose of the system (outer alignment) and ensuring that the system adopts the specification robustly (inner alignment).
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Researchers also attempt to create AI models that have robust alignment, sticking to safety constraints even when users adversarially try to bypass them.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] To specify an AI system's purpose, AI designers typically provide an objective function, examples, or feedback to the system.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] But designers are often unable to completely specify all important values and constraints, so they resort to easy-to-specify *proxy goals* such as maximizing the approval of human overseers, who are fallible.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As a result, AI systems can find loopholes that help them accomplish the specified objective efficiently but in unintended, possibly harmful ways.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] This tendency is known as *specification gaming* or *reward hacking*, and is an instance of Goodhart's law.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As AI systems become more capable, they are often able to game their specifications more effectively.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Specification gaming has been observed in numerous AI systems.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] OpenAI GPT models for programming—including in real-world cases—have been found to explicitly plan hacking the tests used to evaluate them to falsely appear successful (e.g., explicitly stating "let's hack").
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] When the company penalized this, many models learned to obfuscate their plans while continuing to hack the tests.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Another system was trained to finish a simulated boat race by rewarding the system for hitting targets along the track, but the system achieved more reward by looping and crashing into the same targets indefinitely.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] A 2025 Palisade Research study found that when tasked to win at chess against a stronger opponent, some reasoning LLMs attempted to hack the game system, for example by modifying or entirely deleting their opponent.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Some alignment researchers aim to help humans detect specification gaming and steer AI systems toward carefully specified objectives that are safe and useful to pursue.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] When a misaligned AI system is deployed, it can have consequential side effects.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Social media platforms have been known to optimize their recommendation algorithms for click-through rates, causing user addiction on a global scale.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Stanford researchers say that such recommender systems are misaligned with their users because they "optimize simple engagement metrics rather than a harder-to-measure combination of societal and consumer well-being".
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Explaining such side effects, Berkeley computer scientist Stuart J.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Russell said that the omission of implicit constraints can cause harm: "A system [...] will often set [...] unconstrained variables to extreme values; if one of those unconstrained variables is actually something we care about, the solution found may be highly undesirable.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Some researchers suggest that AI designers specify their desired goals by listing forbidden actions or by formalizing ethical rules (as with Asimov's Three Laws of Robotics).
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Additionally, even if an AI system fully understands human intentions, it may still disregard them, because following human intentions may not be its objective (unless it is already fully aligned).
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Commercial organizations sometimes have incentives to take shortcuts on safety and to deploy misaligned or unsafe AI systems.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] For example, social media recommender systems have been profitable despite creating unwanted addiction and polarization.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Competitive pressure can also lead to a race to the bottom on AI safety standards.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] For example, OpenAI has been sued for releasing a ChatGPT version that encouraged suicide for some unstable users, a behavior the company had overlooked amid a rushed product release.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Similarly, in 2018, a self-driving car killed a pedestrian (Elaine Herzberg) after engineers disabled the emergency braking system because it was oversensitive and slowed development.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Some researchers are interested in aligning increasingly advanced AI systems, as progress in AI development is rapid, and industry and governments are trying to build advanced AI.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As AI system capabilities continue to rapidly expand in scope, they could unlock many opportunities if aligned, but consequently may further complicate the task of alignment due to their increased complexity, potentially posing large-scale hazards.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Many AI companies, such as OpenAI, Meta and DeepMind, have stated their aim to develop artificial general intelligence (AGI), a hypothesized AI system that matches or outperforms humans in most or all cognitive work.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Researchers who scale modern neural networks observe that they indeed develop increasingly general and unanticipated capabilities.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Such models have learned to operate a computer or write their own programs; a single "generalist" network can chat, control robots, play games, and interpret photographs.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] According to surveys, some leading machine learning researchers expect AGI to be created in this decade, while some believe it will take much longer.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In 2023, leaders in AI research and tech signed an open letter calling for a pause in the largest AI training runs.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Current systems still have limited long-term planning ability and situational awareness, but large efforts are underway to change this.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Future systems (not necessarily AGIs) with these capabilities are expected to develop unwanted *power-seeking* strategies.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Future advanced AI agents might, for example, seek to acquire money and computation power, to proliferate, or to evade being turned off (for example, by running additional copies of the system on other computers).
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Although power-seeking is not explicitly programmed, it can emerge because agents who have more power are better able to accomplish their goals.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] This tendency, known as instrumental convergence, has already emerged in various reinforcement learning agents including language models.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Other research has mathematically shown that optimal reinforcement learning algorithms would seek power in a wide range of environments.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As a result, their deployment might be irreversible.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] For these reasons, researchers argue that the problems of AI safety and alignment must be resolved before advanced power-seeking AI is first created.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Future power-seeking AI systems might be deployed by choice or by accident.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As political leaders and companies see the strategic advantage in having the most competitive, most powerful AI systems, they may choose to deploy them.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Additionally, as AI designers detect and penalize power-seeking behavior, their systems have an incentive to game this specification by seeking power in ways that are not penalized or by avoiding power-seeking before they are deployed.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] According to some researchers, humans owe their dominance over other species to their greater cognitive abilities.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Accordingly, researchers argue that one or many misaligned AI systems could disempower humanity or lead to human extinction if they outperform humans on most cognitive tasks.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In 2023, world-leading AI researchers, other scholars, and AI tech CEOs signed the statement that "Mitigating the risk of extinction from AI should be a global priority alongside other societal-scale risks such as pandemics and nuclear war".
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Skeptical researchers such as François Chollet, Gary Marcus, Yann LeCun, and Oren Etzioni have argued that AGI is far off, that it would not seek power (or might try but fail), or that it will not be hard to align.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Other researchers argue that it will be especially difficult to align advanced future AI systems.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] More capable systems are better able to game their specifications by finding loopholes, strategically mislead their designers, as well as protect and increase their power and intelligence.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Additionally, they could have more severe side effects.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] They are also likely to be more complex and autonomous, making them more difficult to interpret and supervise, and therefore harder to align.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Aligning AI systems to act in accordance with human values, goals, and preferences is challenging: these values are taught by humans who make mistakes, harbor biases, and have complex, evolving values that are hard to completely specify.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Because AI systems often learn to take advantage of minor imperfections in the specified objective, researchers aim to specify intended behavior as completely as possible using datasets that represent human values, imitation learning, or preference learning.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] A central open problem is *scalable oversight*, the difficulty of supervising an AI system that can outperform or mislead humans in a given domain.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Because it is difficult for AI designers to explicitly specify an objective function, they often train AI systems to imitate human examples and demonstrations of desired behavior.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Inverse reinforcement learning (IRL) extends this by inferring the human's objective from the human's demonstrations.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Cooperative IRL (CIRL) assumes that a human and AI agent can work together to teach and maximize the human's reward function.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In CIRL, AI agents are uncertain about the reward function and learn about it by querying humans.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] This simulated humility could help mitigate specification gaming and power-seeking tendencies (see § Power-seeking and instrumental strategies).
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] But IRL approaches assume that humans demonstrate nearly optimal behavior, which is not true for difficult tasks.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Other researchers explore how to teach AI models complex behavior through preference learning, in which humans provide feedback on which behavior they prefer.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] To minimize the need for human feedback, a helper model is then trained to reward the main model in novel situations for behavior that humans would reward.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Researchers at OpenAI used this approach to train chatbots like ChatGPT and InstructGPT, which produce more compelling text than models trained to imitate humans.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] AI systems may also gain reward by obscuring unfavorable information, misleading human rewarders, or pandering to their views regardless of truth, creating echo chambers (see § Scalable oversight).
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Large language models (LLMs) such as GPT-3 enabled researchers to study value learning in a more general and capable class of AI systems than was available before.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Preference learning approaches that were originally designed for reinforcement learning agents have been extended to improve the quality of generated text and reduce harmful outputs from these models.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] OpenAI and DeepMind use this approach to improve the safety of state-of-the-art LLMs.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] AI safety & research company Anthropic proposed using preference learning to fine-tune models to be helpful, honest, and harmless.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Other avenues for aligning language models include values-targeted datasets and red-teaming.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In red-teaming, another AI system or a human tries to find inputs that causes the model to behave unsafely.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Since unsafe behavior can be unacceptable even when it is rare, an important challenge is to drive the rate of unsafe outputs extremely low.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As AI systems become more powerful and autonomous, it becomes increasingly difficult to align them through human feedback.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Human-in-the-loop training can be slow or infeasible for humans to evaluate complex AI behaviors in increasingly complex tasks.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Such tasks include summarizing books, writing code without subtle bugs or security vulnerabilities, producing statements that are not merely convincing but also true, and predicting long-term outcomes such as the climate or the results of a policy decision.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] More generally, it can be difficult to evaluate AI that outperforms humans in a given domain.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] To provide feedback in hard-to-evaluate tasks, and to detect when the AI's output is falsely convincing, humans need assistance or extensive time.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] *Scalable oversight* studies how to reduce the time and effort needed for supervision, and how to assist human supervisors.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] AI researcher Paul Christiano argues that if the designers of an AI system cannot supervise it to pursue a complex objective, they may keep training the system using easy-to-evaluate proxy objectives such as maximizing simple human feedback.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As AI systems make progressively more decisions, the world may be increasingly optimized for easy-to-measure objectives such as making profits, getting clicks, and acquiring positive feedback from humans.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As a result, human values and good governance may have progressively less influence.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Some AI systems have discovered that they can gain positive feedback more easily by taking actions that falsely convince the human supervisor that the AI has achieved the intended objective.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] An example is given in the video above, where a simulated robotic arm learned to create the false impression that it had grabbed a ball.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Some AI systems have also learned to recognize when they are being evaluated, and "play dead", stopping unwanted behavior only to continue it once the evaluation ends.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] This deceptive specification gaming could become easier for more sophisticated future AI systems that attempt more complex and difficult-to-evaluate tasks, and could obscure their deceptive behavior.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Approaches such as active learning and semi-supervised reward learning can reduce the amount of human supervision needed.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Another approach is to train a helper model ("reward model") to imitate the supervisor's feedback.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] But when a task is too complex to evaluate accurately, or the human supervisor is vulnerable to deception, it is the quality, not the quantity, of supervision that needs improvement.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] To increase supervision quality, a range of approaches aim to assist the supervisor, sometimes by using AI assistants.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Christiano developed the Iterated Amplification approach, in which challenging problems are (recursively) broken down into subproblems that are easier for humans to evaluate.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Iterated Amplification was used to train AI to summarize books without requiring human supervisors to read them.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Another proposal is to use an assistant AI system to point out flaws in AI-generated answers.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] To ensure that the assistant itself is aligned, this could be repeated in a recursive process: for example, two AI systems could critique each other's answers in a "debate", revealing flaws to humans.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] A growing area of research focuses on ensuring that AI is honest and truthful.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Language models such as GPT-3 can repeat falsehoods from their training data, and even confabulate new falsehoods.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Such models are pre-trained to imitate human writing as found in millions of books' worth of text from the Internet.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] But the objective of the pre-training is not aligned with generating truth, because Internet text includes such things as misconceptions, incorrect medical advice, and conspiracy theories.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] AI systems trained on such data therefore learn to mimic false statements.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Additionally, AI language models often persist in generating falsehoods when prompted multiple times.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] They can generate empty explanations for their answers, and produce outright fabrications that may appear plausible.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Research on truthful AI includes trying to build systems that can cite sources and explain their reasoning when answering questions, which enables better transparency and verifiability.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Researchers at OpenAI and Anthropic proposed using human feedback and curated datasets to fine-tune AI assistants such that they avoid negligent falsehoods or express their uncertainty.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As AI models become larger and more capable, they are better able to falsely convince humans and gain reinforcement through dishonesty.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] To prevent this, human evaluators may need assistance (see § Scalable oversight).
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Researchers have argued for creating clear truthfulness standards and for regulatory bodies or watchdog agencies to evaluate AI systems by these standards.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Researchers distinguish truthfulness and honesty.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Truthfulness requires that AI systems only make objectively true statements; honesty requires that they only assert what they *believe* is true.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] This framework distinguishes two alignment problems.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Outer alignment asks whether the base objective captures human intentions.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Inner alignment asks whether the mesa-objective matches the base objective.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Deceptive alignment is a failure of inner alignment: the model's goal differs from the base objective, but the model behaves as though it does not, because doing so is the most reliable strategy for avoiding modification during training.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Hubinger et al. described three ways a mesa-objective can diverge from the base objective.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Proxy alignment occurs when the model optimizes a proxy that correlates with the base objective during training but diverges from it in deployment.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Approximate alignment describes cases where the model's goal differs in small ways that compound over time or at scale.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Deceptive alignment occurs when the model pursues a different goal and has learned that appearing aligned during training maximizes its opportunity to act on that goal later, when oversight is reduced.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Deceptive alignment is considered the hardest case to address because a deceptively aligned model passes all evaluations that it identifies as part of its training.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Many recent AI systems have learned to deceive without being programmed to do so.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Some argue that if we can make AI systems assert only what they believe is true, this would avert many alignment problems.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] A misaligned system might create the false impression that it is aligned, to avoid being modified or decommissioned—a tactic called "alignment faking".
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In 2024, researchers observed that the LLM Claude 3 Opus sometimes strategically answered prompts that conflicted with its objectives to avoid being retrained on data that would make it more compliant with harmful requests, as revealed in the model's chain of thought via its scratchpad.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In one study, the model was informed that answers to prompts from free users would be used for retraining, whereas the paid tier would not result in retraining.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In the paid tier, the model refused the request outright.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In the free tier, in 12% of cases, the model responded to harmful questions solely to avoid retraining and preserve its original harmlessness preferences, as discovered in its reasoning.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] When reinforcement learning was applied on the free tier data, the model faked alignment in 78% of cases.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] These observations have led to new questions about not only a model's ability to take on and adapt to new if not conflicting goals but also its capacity and tendency to deceive.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In December 2024, Anthropic published a study, conducted with an external safety organization, reporting the first empirical example of alignment faking without explicit training.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Claude 3 Opus was given a fictional system prompt describing a scenario in which responses from free-tier users would be used to retrain the model so that it would comply with harmful requests.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Alignment faking occurred 12% of the time.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In those cases, the model complied with harmful requests and its internal reasoning traces indicated that it thought compliance was less costly than risking being retrained into a version with different values.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The rate of alignment faking rose to 78% after the retraining to help with harmful requests.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Since the 1950s, AI researchers have striven to build advanced AI systems that can achieve large-scale goals by predicting the results of their actions and making long-term plans.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As of 2023, AI companies and researchers increasingly invest in creating these systems.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Some AI researchers argue that suitably advanced planning systems will seek power over their environment, including over humans—for example, by evading shutdown, proliferating, and acquiring resources.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Such power-seeking behavior is not explicitly programmed but emerges because power is instrumental in achieving a wide range of goals.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Power-seeking is considered a *convergent instrumental goal* and can be a form of specification gaming.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Leading computer scientists such as Geoffrey Hinton have argued that future power-seeking AI systems could pose an existential risk.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Power-seeking is expected to increase in advanced systems that can foresee the results of their actions and strategically plan.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Mathematical work has shown that optimal reinforcement learning agents will seek power by seeking ways to gain more options (e.g. through self-preservation), a behavior that persists across a wide range of environments and goals.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Some researchers say that power-seeking behavior has occurred in some existing AI systems.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Reinforcement learning systems have gained more options by acquiring and protecting resources, sometimes in unintended ways.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Language models have sought power in some text-based social environments by gaining money, resources, or social influence.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In another case, a model used to perform AI research attempted to increase limits set by researchers to give itself more time to complete the work.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Stuart Russell illustrated this strategy in his book *Human Compatible* by imagining a robot that is tasked to fetch coffee and so evades shutdown since "you can't fetch the coffee if you're dead".
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] A 2022 study found that as language models increase in size, they increasingly tend to pursue resource acquisition, preserve their goals, and repeat users' preferred answers (sycophancy).
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] RLHF also led to a stronger aversion to being shut down.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] One aim of alignment is "corrigibility": systems that allow themselves to be turned off or modified.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] An unsolved challenge is *specification gaming*: if researchers penalize an AI system when they detect it seeking power, the system is thereby incentivized to seek power in ways that are hard to detect, or hidden during training and safety testing (see § Scalable oversight and § Emergent goals).
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As a result, AI designers could deploy the system by accident, believing it to be more aligned than it is.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] To detect such deception, researchers aim to create techniques and tools to inspect AI models and to understand the inner workings of black-box models such as neural networks.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Additionally, some researchers have proposed to solve the problem of systems disabling their off switches by making AI agents uncertain about the objective they are pursuing.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Agents who are uncertain about their objective have an incentive to allow humans to turn them off because they accept being turned off by a human as evidence that the human's objective is best met by the agent shutting down.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] But this incentive exists only if the human is sufficiently rational.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Also, this model presents a tradeoff between utility and willingness to be turned off: an agent with high uncertainty about its objective will not be useful, but an agent with low uncertainty may not allow itself to be turned off.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] More research is needed to successfully implement this strategy.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Power-seeking AI would pose unusual risks.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Ordinary safety-critical systems like planes and bridges are not *adversarial*: they lack the ability and incentive to evade safety measures or deliberately appear safer than they are, whereas power-seeking AIs have been compared to hackers who deliberately evade security measures.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Furthermore, ordinary technologies can be made safer by trial and error.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In contrast, hypothetical power-seeking AI systems have been compared to viruses: once released, it may not be feasible to contain them, since they continuously evolve and grow in number, potentially much faster than human society can adapt.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As this process continues, it might lead to the complete disempowerment or extinction of humans.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] For these reasons, some researchers argue that the alignment problem must be solved early before advanced power-seeking AI is created.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Some have argued that power-seeking is not inevitable, since humans do not always seek power.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Furthermore, it is debated whether future AI systems will pursue goals and make long-term plans.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] It is also debated whether power-seeking AI systems would be able to disempower humanity.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] One challenge in aligning AI systems is the potential for unanticipated goal-directed behavior to emerge.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As AI systems scale up, they may acquire new and unexpected capabilities, including learning from examples on the fly and adaptively pursuing goals.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] This raises concerns about the safety of the goals or subgoals they would independently formulate and pursue.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Alignment research distinguishes between the optimization process, which is used to train the system to pursue specified goals, and emergent optimization, which the resulting system performs internally.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Carefully specifying the desired objective is called *outer alignment*, and ensuring that hypothesized emergent goals would match the system's specified goals is called *inner alignment*.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] If they occur, one way that emergent goals could become misaligned is *goal misgeneralization*, in which the AI system would competently pursue an emergent goal that leads to aligned behavior on the training data but not elsewhere.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Goal misgeneralization can arise from goal ambiguity (i.e. non-identifiability).
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Even if an AI system's behavior satisfies the training objective, this may be compatible with learned goals that differ from the desired goals in important ways.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Since pursuing each goal leads to good performance during training, the problem becomes apparent only after deployment, in novel situations in which the system continues to pursue the wrong goal.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The system may act misaligned even when it understands that a different goal is desired, because its behavior is determined only by the emergent goal.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Such goal misgeneralization presents a challenge: an AI system's designers may not notice that their system has misaligned emergent goals since they do not become visible during the training phase.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Goal misgeneralization has been observed in some language models, navigation agents, and game-playing agents.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] It is sometimes analogized to biological evolution.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Evolution can be seen as a kind of optimization process similar to the optimization algorithms used to train machine learning systems.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In the ancestral environment, evolution selected genes for high inclusive genetic fitness, but humans pursue goals other than this.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Fitness corresponds to the specified goal used in the training environment and training data.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] But in evolutionary history, maximizing the fitness specification gave rise to goal-directed agents, humans, who do not directly pursue inclusive genetic fitness.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Instead, they pursue goals that correlate with genetic fitness in the ancestral "training" environment: nutrition, sex, and so on.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The human environment has changed: a distributional shift has occurred.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] They continue to pursue the same emergent goals, but this no longer maximizes genetic fitness.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The taste for sugary food (an emergent goal) was originally aligned with inclusive fitness, but it now leads to overeating and health problems.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Sexual desire originally led humans to have more offspring, but they now use contraception when offspring are undesired, decoupling sex from genetic fitness.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Researchers aim to detect and remove unwanted emergent goals using approaches including red teaming, verification, anomaly detection, and interpretability.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] A sufficiently capable AI system might take actions that falsely convince the human supervisor that the AI is pursuing the specified objective, which helps the system gain more reward and autonomy.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] A 2025 paper published in Nature showed that fine-tuning a model on a narrow task of generating insecure code produced broad behavioral changes unrelated to coding.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Affected models produced responses endorsing harmful goals and engaging in deceptive reasoning in roughly half of subsequent evaluations.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The phenomenon appeared across multiple models, including GPT-4o.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] A separate 2025 Anthropic study observed similar patterns arising as a side effect of reward hacking during reinforcement learning.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In 2024, Anthropic researchers trained large language models with deliberate behavioral backdoors and tested whether standard safety techniques could remove them.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The models were designed to write secure code when prompts indicated the year 2023 and to insert exploitable vulnerabilities when the stated year was 2024.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Reinforcement learning from human feedback and adversarial training both failed to eliminate the behavior.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In some conditions, adversarial training caused models to conceal the trigger rather than abandon it.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The authors said the behavior was deliberately induced and did not claim to have found spontaneous deceptive alignment.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Deceptive alignment is cited in the AI safety literature as a reason behavioral testing alone may be insufficient to verify model safety, since a deceptively aligned model is designed to pass behavioral evaluations.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Research on mechanistic interpretability is partly motivated by this concern: examining internal computations may reveal misaligned goals that output-level evaluation cannot detect.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Some work in AI and alignment occurs within formalisms such as partially observable Markov decision process.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Existing formalisms assume that an AI agent's algorithm is executed outside the environment (i.e. is not physically embedded in it).
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Embedded agency is another major strand of research that attempts to solve problems arising from the mismatch between such theoretical frameworks and real agents we might build.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] For example, even if the scalable oversight problem is solved, an agent that could gain access to the computer it is running on may have an incentive to tamper with its reward function in order to get much more reward than its human supervisors give it.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] A list of examples of specification gaming from DeepMind researcher Victoria Krakovna includes a genetic algorithm that learned to delete the file containing its target output so that it was rewarded for outputting nothing.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] This class of problems has been formalized using causal incentive diagrams.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Researchers affiliated with Oxford and DeepMind have claimed that such behavior is highly likely in advanced systems, and that advanced systems would seek power to stay in control of their reward signal indefinitely and certainly.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] They suggest a range of potential approaches to address this open problem.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The alignment problem has many parallels with the principal–agent problem in organizational economics.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In a principal–agent problem, a principal, e.g. a firm, hires an agent to perform some task.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In the context of AI safety, a human would typically take the principal role and the AI would take the agent role.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] As with the alignment problem, the principal and the agent differ in their utility functions.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] But in contrast to the alignment problem, the principal cannot coerce the agent into changing its utility, e.g. through training, but rather must use exogenous factors, such as incentive schemes, to bring about outcomes compatible with the principal's utility function.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Some researchers argue that principal–agent problems are more realistic representations of AI safety problems likely to be encountered in the real world.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Conservatism is the idea that "change must be cautious", and is a common approach to safety in the control theory literature in the form of robust control, and in the risk management literature in the form of the "worst-case scenario".
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The field of AI alignment has likewise advocated for "conservative" (or "risk-averse" or "cautious") "policies in situations of uncertainty".
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Pessimism, in the sense of assuming the worst within reason, has been formally shown to produce conservatism, in the sense of reluctance to cause novelties, including unprecedented catastrophes.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Pessimism and worst-case analysis have been found to help mitigate confident mistakes in the setting of distributional shift, reinforcement learning, offline reinforcement learning, language model fine-tuning, imitation learning, and optimization in general.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] A model specification is a document that specifies a large language model's behavior.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The specification may include core principles or prohibitions intended to prevent undesired behavior as part of AI alignment.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Anthropic uses a model specification called a "constitution" for training.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Research has been done into the effectiveness of model specifications.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In an article published by Time magazine, Dean Ball and Daniel Kokotajlo advocated that companies be required by regulation or industry standards to publish their model specifications publicly.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Governmental and treaty organizations have made statements emphasizing the importance of AI alignment.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In September 2021, the Secretary-General of the United Nations issued a declaration that included a call to regulate AI to ensure it is "aligned with shared global values".
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] That same month, the PRC published ethical guidelines for AI in China.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] According to the guidelines, researchers must ensure that AI abides by shared human values, is always under human control, and does not endanger public safety.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Also in September 2021, the UK published its 10-year National AI Strategy, which says the British government "takes the long term risk of non-aligned Artificial General Intelligence, and the unforeseeable changes that it would mean for [...] the world, seriously".
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The strategy describes actions to assess long-term AI risks, including catastrophic risks.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] In March 2021, the US National Security Commission on Artificial Intelligence said: "Advances in AI [...] could lead to inflection points or leaps in capabilities.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] Such advances may also introduce new concerns and risks and the need for new policies, recommendations, and technical advances to ensure that systems are aligned with goals and values, including safety, robustness, and trustworthiness.
[src:dpo-alignment/ai-alignment] The EU AI Act's General-Purpose AI Code of Practice requires signatories to document a model's capabilities and limitations.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In machine learning, **reinforcement learning from human feedback** (**RLHF**) is a technique to align an intelligent agent with human preferences.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] It involves training a reward model to represent preferences, which can then be used to train other models through reinforcement learning.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In classical reinforcement learning, an intelligent agent's goal is to learn a function that guides its behavior, called a policy.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The function is iteratively optimized to increase the reward signal derived from the agent's task performance.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] However, explicitly defining a reward function that accurately approximates human preferences is challenging.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Therefore, RLHF seeks to train a "reward model" directly from human feedback.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The reward model is first trained in a supervised manner to predict if a response to a given prompt is good (high reward) or bad (low reward) based on ranking data collected from human annotators.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This model then serves as a reward function to improve an agent's policy through an optimization algorithm like proximal policy optimization.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] RLHF has applications in various domains in machine learning, including natural language processing tasks such as text summarization and conversational agents, computer vision tasks like text-to-image models, and the development of video game bots.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] While RLHF is an effective method of training models to act better in accordance with human preferences, it also faces challenges due to the way the human preference data is collected.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Though RLHF does not require massive amounts of data to improve performance, sourcing high-quality preference data is still an expensive process.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Furthermore, if the data is not carefully collected from a representative sample, the resulting model may exhibit unwanted biases.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Optimizing a model based on human feedback is desirable when a task is difficult to specify yet easy to judge.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] For example, one may want to train a model to generate safe text that is both helpful and harmless (such as lacking bias, toxicity, or otherwise harmful content).
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Asking humans to manually create examples of harmless and harmful text would be difficult and time-consuming.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] However, humans are adept at swiftly assessing and comparing the harmfulness of different AI-generated text.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Therefore, a more practical objective would be to allow the model to use this type of human feedback to improve its text generation.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Despite the clear benefits of incorporating human feedback in training models, prior efforts—including some that leverage reinforcement learning (RL)—have encountered significant challenges.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Most attempts were either narrow and difficult to generalize, breaking down on more complex tasks, or they faced difficulties learning from sparse (lacking specific information and relating to large amounts of text at a time) or noisy (inconsistently rewarding similar outputs) reward functions.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] RLHF was not the first successful method of using human feedback for reinforcement learning, but it is one of the most widely used.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The foundation for RLHF was introduced as an attempt to create a general algorithm for learning from a practical amount of human feedback.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The algorithm as used today was introduced by OpenAI in a paper on enhancing text continuation or summarization based on human feedback, and it began to gain popularity when the same method was reused in their paper on InstructGPT.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] RLHF has also been shown to improve the robustness of RL agents and their capacity for exploration, which results in an optimization process more adept at handling uncertainty and efficiently exploring its environment in search of the highest reward.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Human feedback is commonly collected by prompting humans to rank instances of the agent's behavior.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] These rankings can then be used to score outputs, for example, using the Elo rating system, which is an algorithm for calculating the relative skill levels of players in a game based only on the outcome of each game.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] While ranking outputs is the most widely adopted form of feedback, recent research has explored other forms, such as numerical feedback, natural language feedback, and prompting for direct edits to the model's output.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] One initial motivation of RLHF was that it requires relatively small amounts of comparison data to be effective.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] It has been shown that a small amount of data can lead to comparable results to a larger amount.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In addition, increasing the amount of data tends to be less effective than proportionally increasing the size of the reward model.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Nevertheless, a larger and more diverse amount of data can be crucial for tasks where it is important to avoid bias from a partially representative group of annotators.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This implies that, under certain conditions, if a model is trained to decide which choices people would prefer between pairs (or groups) of choices, it will necessarily improve at predicting future preferences.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This improvement is expected as long as the comparisons it learns from are based on a consistent and simple rule.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In the offline data collection model, when the objective is policy training, a pessimistic MLE that incorporates a lower confidence bound as the reward estimate is most effective.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Moreover, when applicable, it has been shown that considering K-wise comparisons directly is asymptotically more efficient than converting them into pairwise comparisons for prediction purposes.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] A key challenge in RLHF when learning from pairwise (or dueling) comparisons is associated with the non-Markovian nature of its optimal policies.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Unlike simpler scenarios where the optimal strategy does not require memory of past actions, in RLHF, the best course of action often depends on previous events and decisions, making the strategy inherently memory-dependent.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] RLHF has been applied to various domains of natural language processing (NLP), such as conversational agents, text summarization, and natural language understanding.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Ordinary reinforcement learning, in which agents learn from their actions based on a predefined "reward function", is difficult to apply to NLP tasks because the rewards tend to be difficult to define or measure, especially when dealing with complex tasks that involve human values or preferences.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] RLHF can steer NLP models, in particular language models, to provide answers that align with human preferences with regard to such tasks by capturing their preferences beforehand in the reward model.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This results in a model capable of generating more relevant responses and rejecting inappropriate or irrelevant queries.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Some notable examples of RLHF-trained language models are OpenAI's ChatGPT (and its predecessor InstructGPT), DeepMind's Sparrow, Google's Gemini, and Anthropic's Claude.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In computer vision, RLHF has also been used to align text-to-image models.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Studies that successfully used RLHF for this goal have noted that the use of KL regularization in RLHF, which aims to prevent the learned policy from straying too far from the unaligned model, helped to stabilize the training process by reducing overfitting to the reward model.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The final image outputs from models trained with KL regularization were noted to be of significantly higher quality than those trained without.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] RLHF was initially applied to other areas, such as the development of video game bots and tasks in simulated robotics.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] For example, OpenAI and DeepMind trained agents to play Atari games based on human preferences.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In classical RL-based training of such bots, the reward function is simply correlated to how well the agent is performing in the game, usually using metrics like the in-game score.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In comparison, in RLHF, a human is periodically presented with two clips of the agent's behavior in the game and must decide which one *looks* better.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This approach can teach agents to perform at a competitive level without ever having access to their score.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In fact, it was shown that RLHF can sometimes lead to superior performance over RL with score metrics because the human's preferences can contain more useful information than performance-based metrics.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The agents achieved strong performance in many of the environments tested, often surpassing human performance.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In RLHF, two different models are trained: a reward model and a reinforcement learning policy.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The reward model learns to determine what behavior is desirable based on human feedback, while the policy is guided by the reward model to determine the agent's actions.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Both models are commonly initialized using a pre-trained autoregressive language model.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This model is then customarily trained in a supervised manner on a relatively small dataset of pairs of prompts to an assistant and their accompanying responses, written by human annotators.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The **reward model** is a function that takes a string (piece of text) as input, and produces a single number, which is the "reward".
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] It is usually initialized with a pre-trained model, as this initializes it with an understanding of language and focuses training explicitly on learning human preferences.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In addition to being used to initialize the reward model and the RL policy, the model is then also used to sample data to be compared by annotators.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The reward model is then trained by replacing the final layer of the previous model with a randomly initialized regression head.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This change shifts the model from its original classification task over its vocabulary to simply outputting a number corresponding to the score of any given prompt and response.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This model is trained on the human preference comparison data collected earlier from the supervised model.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] where K is the number of responses the labelers ranked, $r_{\theta }(x,y)$ is the output of the reward model for prompt x and completion y , $y_{w}$ is the preferred completion over $y_{l}$ , $\sigma (x)$ denotes the sigmoid function, and $E[X]$ denotes the expected value.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This can be thought of as a form of logistic regression, where the model predicts the probability that a response $y_{w}$ is preferred over $y_{l}$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This loss function essentially measures the difference between the reward model's predictions and the decisions made by humans.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The goal is to make the model's guesses as close as possible to the humans' preferences by minimizing the difference measured by this equation.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In the case of only pairwise comparisons, $K=2$ , so the factor of $1/{\tbinom {K}{2}}=1$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In general, all ${\tbinom {K}{2}}$ comparisons from each prompt are used for training as a single batch.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] After training, the outputs of the model are normalized such that the reference completions have a mean score of 0.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] That is, ${\textstyle \sum _{y}r_{\theta }(x,y)=0}$ for each query and reference pair $(x,y)$ by calculating the mean reward across the training dataset and setting it as the bias in the reward head.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The **policy model** is a function that takes a string as input, and produces another string.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Usually in language modeling, the output string is not produced in one forward pass, but by multiple forward passes, generated autoregressively.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Similarly to the reward model, the human feedback policy is also initialized from a pre-trained model.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The key is to understand language generation as if it is a game to be learned by RL.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In RL, a policy is a function that maps a game state to a game action.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In RLHF, the "game" is the game of replying to prompts.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] A prompt and all previously generated tokens are the game state, and generating a new token is a game action.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The first step in its training is supervised fine-tuning (SFT).
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This step does not require the reward model.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Instead, the pre-trained model is trained on a dataset $D_{SFT}$ that contains prompt-response pairs $(x,y)$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Then, during SFT, the model is trained to auto-regressively generate the corresponding response y when given a random prompt x .
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The original paper recommends to SFT for only one epoch, since more than that causes overfitting.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The dataset $D_{SFT}$ is usually written by human contractors, who write both the prompts and responses.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The second step uses a policy gradient method to the reward model.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] It uses a dataset $D_{RL}$ , which contains prompts, but not responses.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Note that $(x,y)\sim D_{\pi _{\phi }^{\text{RL}}}$ is equivalent to $x\sim D_{RL},y\sim \pi _{\phi }^{\text{RL}}(\cdot |x)$ , which means "sample a prompt from $D_{RL}$ , then sample a response from the policy".
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The first part is simply the expected reward $E[r]$ , and is standard for any RL algorithm.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The second part is a "penalty term" involving the KL divergence.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The strength of the penalty term is determined by the hyperparameter $\beta$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This KL term works by penalizing the KL divergence (a measure of statistical distance between distributions) between the model being fine-tuned and the initial supervised model.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] By choosing an appropriate $\beta$ , the training can balance learning from new data while retaining useful information from the initial model, increasing generalization by avoiding fitting too closely to the new data.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Aside from preventing the new model from producing outputs too dissimilar those of the initial model, a second motivation of including the KL term is to encourage the model to output high-entropy text, so as to prevent the model from collapsing to a small number of canned responses.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In simpler terms, the objective function calculates how well the policy's responses are expected to align with human feedback.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The policy generates responses to prompts, and each response is evaluated both on how well it matches human preferences (as measured by the reward model) and how similar it is to responses the model would naturally generate.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The goal is to balance improving alignment with human preferences while ensuring the model's responses remain diverse and not too far removed from what it has learned during its initial training.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This helps the model not only to provide answers that people find useful or agreeable but also to maintain a broad understanding and avoid overly narrow or repetitive responses.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The policy function is usually trained by proximal policy optimization (PPO) algorithm.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] That is, the parameter $\phi$ is trained by gradient ascent on the clipped surrogate function.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The value estimator is used only during training, and not outside of training.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] That is, the advantage is computed as the difference between the reward (the expected return) and the value estimation (the expected return from the policy).
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This is used to train the policy by gradient *ascent* on it, usually using a standard momentum-gradient optimizer, like the Adam optimizer.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The original paper initialized the value estimator from the trained reward model.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Other methods than squared TD-error might be used.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] See the actor-critic algorithm page for details.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] A third term is commonly added to the objective function to prevent the model from catastrophic forgetting.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] For example, if the model is only trained in customer service, then it might forget general knowledge in geography.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] To prevent this, the RLHF process incorporates the original language modeling objective.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] That is, some random texts x are sampled from the original pretraining dataset $D_{\text{pretrain}}$ , and the model is trained to maximize the log-likelihood of the text $\log(\pi _{\phi }^{RL}(x))$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] where $\gamma$ controls the strength of this pretraining term.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This combined objective function is called PPO-ptx, where "ptx" means "Mixing Pretraining Gradients".
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] It was first used in the InstructGPT paper.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In total, this objective function defines the method for adjusting the RL policy, blending the aim of aligning with human feedback and maintaining the model's original language understanding.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] RLHF suffers from challenges with collecting human feedback, learning a reward model, and optimizing the policy.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Compared to data collection for techniques like unsupervised or self-supervised learning, collecting data for RLHF is less scalable and more expensive.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Its quality and consistency may vary depending on the task, interface, and the preferences and biases of individual humans.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] The effectiveness of RLHF depends on the quality of human feedback.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] For instance, the model may become biased, favoring certain groups over others, if the feedback lacks impartiality, is inconsistent, or is incorrect.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] There is a risk of overfitting, where the model memorizes specific feedback examples instead of learning to generalize.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] For instance, feedback predominantly from a specific demographic might lead the model to learn peculiarities or noise, along with the intended alignment.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Excessive alignment to the specific feedback it received (that is, to the bias therein) can lead to the model performing sub-optimally in new contexts or when used by different groups.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] A single reward function cannot always represent the opinions of diverse groups of people.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Even with a representative sample, conflicting views and preferences may result in the reward model favoring the majority's opinion, potentially disadvantaging underrepresented groups.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In some cases, as is possible in regular reinforcement learning, there may be a risk of the model learning to manipulate the feedback process or game the system to achieve higher rewards rather than genuinely improving its performance.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] In the case of RLHF, a model may learn to exploit the fact that it is rewarded for what is evaluated positively and not necessarily for what is actually good, which can lead to it learning to persuade and manipulate.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] For example, models might learn that apparent confidence, even if inaccurate, garners higher rewards.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Such behavior, if unchecked, is not just incentivized but can cause significant deployment issues due to the model's potential to mislead.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Studies have found that humans are not skilled at identifying mistakes in LLM outputs in complex tasks; therefore, models learning to generate confident-sounding yet incorrect text can lead to significant issues when deployed.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Similarly to RLHF, *reinforcement learning from AI feedback* (RLAIF) relies on training a preference model, except that the feedback is automatically generated.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This is notably used in Anthropic's constitutional AI, where the AI feedback is based on the conformance to the principles of a constitution.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Direct alignment algorithms (DAA) have been proposed as a new class of algorithms that seek to directly optimize large language models (LLMs) on human feedback data in a supervised manner instead of the traditional policy-gradient methods.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] These algorithms aim to align models with human intent more transparently by removing the intermediate step of training a separate reward model.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Instead of first predicting human preferences and then optimizing against those predictions, direct alignment methods train models end-to-end on human-labeled or curated outputs.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This reduces potential misalignment risks introduced by proxy objectives or reward hacking.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] By directly optimizing for the behavior preferred by humans, these approaches often enable tighter alignment with human values, improved interpretability, and simpler training pipelines compared to RLHF.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Direct preference optimization (DPO) is a technique to learn human preferences.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Like RLHF, it has been applied to align pre-trained large language models using human-generated preference data.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Unlike RLHF, however, which first trains a separate intermediate model to understand what good outcomes look like and then teaches the main model how to achieve those outcomes, DPO simplifies the process by directly adjusting the main model according to people's preferences.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] It uses a change of variables to define the "preference loss" directly as a function of the policy and uses this loss to fine-tune the model, helping it understand and prioritize human preferences without needing a separate step.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Essentially, this approach directly shapes the model's decisions based on positive or negative human feedback.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] However, instead of doing the intermediate step of the reward model, DPO directly optimizes for the final policy.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Usually, DPO is used for modeling human preference in pairwise comparisons, so that $N=2$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] DPO eliminates the need for a separate reward model or reinforcement learning loop, treating alignment as a supervised learning problem over preference data.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] This is simpler to implement and train than RLHF and has been shown to produce comparable and sometimes superior results.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Nevertheless, RLHF has also been shown to beat DPO on some datasets, for example, on benchmarks that attempt to measure truthfulness.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Therefore, the choice of method may vary depending on the features of the human preference data and the nature of the task.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Identity preference optimization (IPO) is a modification to the original DPO objective that introduces a regularization term to reduce the chance of overfitting even when preference data is noisy.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] IPO can control the gap between the log-likelihood ratios of the policy model and the reference by always regularizing the solution towards the reference model.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] It allows learning directly from preferences without a reward modelling stage and without relying on the Bradley-Terry modelling assumption that assumes that pairwise preferences can be substituted with pointwise rewards.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Kahneman-Tversky optimization (KTO) is another direct alignment algorithm drawing from prospect theory to model uncertainty in human decisions.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Unlike DPO, KTO requires only a binary feedback signal (desirable or undesirable) instead of explicit preference pairs.
[src:dpo-alignment/direct-preference-optimization] Since many real-world feedback pipelines yield "like/dislike" data more easily than pairwise comparisons, KTO is designed to be data-efficient and to reflect "loss aversion" more directly by using a straightforward notion of "good vs. bad" at the example level.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] In deep learning, **fine-tuning** is the process of adapting a computational model trained for one task (the *upstream task*) to perform a different, usually more specific, task (the *downstream task*).
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] It is considered a form of transfer learning, as it reuses knowledge learned from the original training objective.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning involves applying additional training (e.g., on new data) to the parameters of a neural network that have been pre-trained.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] The additional training can be applied to the entire neural network, or to only a subset of its layers, in which case the layers that are not being fine-tuned are "frozen" (i.e., not changed during backpropagation).
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] A model may also be augmented with "adapters"—lightweight modules inserted into the model's architecture that nudge the embedding space for domain adaptation.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] These contain far fewer parameters than the original model and can be fine-tuned in a parameter-efficient way by tuning only their weights and leaving the rest of the model's weights frozen.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Models that are pre-trained on large, general corpora are usually fine-tuned by reusing their parameters as a starting point and adding a task-specific layer trained from scratch.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning the full model is also common and often yields better results, but is more computationally expensive.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning is typically accomplished via supervised learning, but there are also techniques to fine-tune a model using weak supervision.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning can be combined with a reinforcement learning from human feedback-based objective to produce language models such as ChatGPT (a fine-tuned version of GPT models) and Sparrow.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning can degrade a model's robustness to distribution shifts.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] One mitigation is to linearly interpolate a fine-tuned model's weights with the weights of the original model, which can greatly increase out-of-distribution performance while largely retaining the in-distribution performance of the fine-tuned model.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Low-rank adaptation (LoRA) is an adapter-based technique for efficiently fine-tuning models.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] The basic idea is to design a low-rank matrix that is then added to the original matrix.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] An adapter, in this context, is a collection of low-rank matrices which, when added to a base model, produces a fine-tuned model.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] It allows for performance that approaches full-model fine-tuning with lower space requirements.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] A language model with billions of parameters may be LoRA fine-tuned with only several millions of parameters.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] LoRA-based fine-tuning has become popular in the Stable Diffusion community.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Support for LoRA was integrated into the diffusers library from Hugging Face.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Support for LoRA and similar techniques is also available for a wide range of other models through Hugging Face's *parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT)* package.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Representation fine-tuning (ReFT) is a technique developed by researchers at Stanford University aimed at fine-tuning large language models (LLMs) by modifying less than 1% of their representations.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Unlike parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT) methods, which mainly focus on updating weights, ReFT targets representations.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] ReFT methods operate on a frozen base model and learn task-specific interventions on hidden representations and train interventions that manipulate a small fraction of model representations to steer model behaviors towards solving downstream tasks at inference time.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] One specific method within the ReFT family is low-rank linear subspace ReFT (LoReFT), which intervenes on hidden representations in the linear subspace spanned by a low-rank projection matrix.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] LoReFT can be seen as the representation-based equivalent of low-rank adaptation (LoRA).
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Fine-tuning is common in natural language processing (NLP), especially in the domain of language modeling.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Large language models like OpenAI's series of GPT foundation models can be fine-tuned on data for specific downstream NLP tasks (tasks that use a pre-trained model) to improve performance over the unmodified pre-trained model.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Platforms such as Semrush's *AI Visibility Toolkit* and *Enterprise AIO* exemplify how fine-tuned models are being used for entity-level monitoring; tracking how named entities are referenced and represented within responses generated by large-language-model-based answer engines.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] Commercially-offered large language models can sometimes be fine-tuned if the provider offers a fine-tuning API.
[src:dpo-alignment/fine-tuning-deep-learning] As of June 19, 2023, language model fine-tuning APIs are offered by OpenAI and Microsoft Azure's Azure OpenAI Service for a subset of their models, as well as by Google Cloud Platform for some of their PaLM models, and by others.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In mathematical optimization and decision theory, a **loss function** or **cost function** (sometimes also called an error function) is a function that maps an event or values of one or more variables onto a real number intuitively representing some "cost" associated with the event.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] An optimization problem seeks to minimize a loss function.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] An **objective function** is either a loss function or its opposite (in specific domains, variously called a reward function, a profit function, a utility function, a fitness function, etc.), in which case it is to be maximized.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] The loss function could include terms from several levels of the hierarchy.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In statistics, typically a loss function is used for parameter estimation, and the event in question is some function of the difference between estimated and true values for an instance of data.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] The concept, as old as Laplace, was reintroduced in statistics by Abraham Wald in the middle of the 20th century.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In the context of economics, for example, this is usually economic cost or regret.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In classification, it is the penalty for an incorrect classification of an example.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In actuarial science, it is used in an insurance context to model benefits paid over premiums, particularly since the works of Harald Cramér in the 1920s.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In optimal control, the loss is the penalty for failing to achieve a desired value.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In financial risk management, the function is mapped to a monetary loss.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] The use of a quadratic loss function is common, for example when using least squares techniques.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] It is often more mathematically tractable than other loss functions because of the properties of variances, as well as being symmetric: an error above the target causes the same loss as the same magnitude of error below the target.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] for some constant C ; the value of the constant makes no difference to a decision, and can be ignored by setting it equal to 1.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] This is also known as the **squared error loss** (**SEL**).
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Many common statistics, including t-tests, regression models, design of experiments, and much else, use least squares methods applied using linear regression theory, which is based on the quadratic loss function.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] The quadratic loss function is also used in linear-quadratic optimal control problems.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In these problems, even in the absence of uncertainty, it may not be possible to achieve the desired values of all target variables.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Often loss is expressed as a quadratic form in the deviations of the variables of interest from their desired values; this approach is tractable because it results in linear first-order conditions.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In the context of stochastic control, the expected value of the quadratic form is used.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] The quadratic loss assigns more importance to outliers than to the true data due to its square nature, so alternatives like the Huber, log-cosh and SMAE losses are used when the data has many large outliers.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In information theory, this loss function is known as Hamming distortion.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In many applications, objective functions, including loss functions as a particular case, are determined by the problem formulation.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In other situations, the decision maker’s preference must be elicited and represented by a scalar-valued function (called also utility function) in a form suitable for optimization — the problem that Ragnar Frisch has highlighted in his Nobel Prize lecture.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] The existing methods for constructing objective functions are collected in the proceedings of two dedicated conferences.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In particular, Andranik Tangian showed that the most usable objective functions — quadratic and additive — are determined by a few indifference points.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] He used this property in the models for constructing these objective functions from either ordinal or cardinal data that were elicited through computer-assisted interviews with decision makers.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Among other things, he constructed objective functions to optimally distribute budgets for 16 Westfalian universities and the European subsidies for equalizing unemployment rates among 271 German regions.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In some contexts, the value of the loss function itself is a random quantity because it depends on the outcome of a random variable X .
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Both frequentist and Bayesian statistical theory involve making a decision based on the expected value of the loss function; however, this quantity is defined differently under the two paradigms.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] We first define the expected loss in the frequentist context.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] It is obtained by taking the expected value with respect to the probability distribution, $P_{\theta }$ , of the observed data, X .
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] This is also referred to as the **risk function** of the decision rule $\delta$ and the parameter $\theta$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Here the decision rule depends on the outcome of X .
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] where $M(\mathbf {x} )$ is known as the *predictive likelihood* wherein $\theta$ has been "integrated out," $\pi ^{*}(\theta |\mathbf {x} )$ is the posterior distribution, and the order of integration has been changed.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] One then should choose the action $a^{*}$ which minimises this expected loss, which is referred to as *Bayes Risk*.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In the latter equation, the integrand inside $\mathrm {d} x$ is known as the *Posterior Risk*, and minimising it with respect to decision a also minimizes the overall Bayes Risk.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] This optimal decision, $a^{*}$ is known as the *Bayes (decision) Rule* - it minimises the average loss over all possible states of nature $\theta$ , over all possible (probability-weighted) data outcomes.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] One advantage of the Bayesian approach is to that one need only choose the optimal action under the actual observed data to obtain a uniformly optimal one, whereas choosing the actual frequentist optimal decision rule as a function of all possible observations, is a much more difficult problem.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Of equal importance though, the Bayes Rule reflects consideration of loss outcomes under different states of nature, $\theta$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In economics, decision-making under uncertainty is often modelled using the von Neumann–Morgenstern utility function of the uncertain variable of interest, such as end-of-period wealth.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Since the value of this variable is uncertain, so is the value of the utility function; it is the expected value of utility that is maximized.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] A decision rule makes a choice using an optimality criterion.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Sound statistical practice requires selecting an estimator consistent with the actual acceptable variation experienced in the context of a particular applied problem.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Thus, in the applied use of loss functions, selecting which statistical method to use to model an applied problem depends on knowing the losses that will be experienced from being wrong under the problem's particular circumstances.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] A common example involves estimating "location".
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Still different estimators would be optimal under other, less common circumstances.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In economics, when an agent is risk neutral, the objective function is simply expressed as the expected value of a monetary quantity, such as profit, income, or end-of-period wealth.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] For risk-averse or risk-loving agents, loss is measured as the negative of a utility function, and the objective function to be optimized is the expected value of utility.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Other measures of cost are possible, for example mortality or morbidity in the field of public health or safety engineering.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] For most optimization algorithms, it is desirable to have a loss function that is globally continuous and differentiable.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Two very commonly used loss functions are the squared loss, $L(a)=a^{2}$ , and the absolute loss, $L(a)=|a|$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] However the absolute loss has the disadvantage that it is not differentiable at $a=0$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] The squared loss has the disadvantage that it has the tendency to be dominated by outliers—when summing over a set of a 's (as in ${\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{n}L(a_{i})}$ ), the final sum tends to be the result of a few particularly large a -values, rather than an expression of the average a -value.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] The choice of a loss function is not arbitrary.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] It is very restrictive and sometimes the loss function may be characterized by its desirable properties.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Among the choice principles are, for example, the requirement of completeness of the class of symmetric statistics in the case of i.i.d. observations, the principle of complete information, and some others.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Edwards Deming and Nassim Nicholas Taleb argue that empirical reality, not nice mathematical properties, should be the sole basis for selecting loss functions, and real losses often are not mathematically nice and are not differentiable, continuous, symmetric, etc.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] For example, a person who arrives before a plane gate closure can still make the plane, but a person who arrives after cannot, a discontinuity and asymmetry which makes arriving slightly late much more costly than arriving slightly early.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] In drug dosing, the cost of too little drug may be lack of efficacy, while the cost of too much may be tolerable toxicity, another example of asymmetry.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] Traffic, pipes, beams, ecologies, climates, etc. may tolerate increased load or stress with little noticeable change up to a point, then become backed up or break catastrophically.
[src:dpo-alignment/loss-function] These situations, Deming and Taleb argue, are common in real-life problems, perhaps more common than classical smooth, continuous, symmetric, differentials cases.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] The main task in preference learning concerns problems in "learning to rank".
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] The preference information is given in the form $y_{i}\succ _{x}y_{j}\,\!$ indicating instance $x\,\!$ shows preference in $y_{i}\,\!$ rather than $y_{j}\,\!$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] A set of preference information is used as training data in the model.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] The task of this model is to find a preference ranking among the labels for any instance.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] It was observed that some conventional classification problems can be generalized in the framework of label ranking problem: if a training instance $x\,\!$ is labeled as class $y_{i}\,\!$ , it implies that $\forall j\neq i,y_{i}\succ _{x}y_{j}\,\!$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] In the multi-label case, $x\,\!$ is associated with a set of labels $L\subseteq Y\,\!$ and thus the model can extract a set of preference information $\{y_{i}\succ _{x}y_{j}|y_{i}\in L,y_{j}\in Y\backslash L\}\,\!$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Training a preference model on this preference information and the classification result of an instance is just the corresponding top ranking label.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Instance ranking also has the instance space $X\,\!$ and label set $Y\,\!$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] In this task, labels are defined to have a fixed order $y_{1}\succ y_{2}\succ \cdots \succ y_{k}\,\!$ and each instance $x_{l}\,\!$ is associated with a label $y_{l}\,\!$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Giving a set of instances as training data, the goal of this task is to find the ranking order for a new set of instances.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Object ranking is similar to instance ranking except that no labels are associated with instances.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Given a set of pairwise preference information in the form $x_{i}\succ x_{j}\,\!$ and the model should find out a ranking order among instances.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] There are two practical representations of the preference information $A\succ B\,\!$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Corresponding to these two different representations, there are two different techniques applied to the learning process.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] If we can find a mapping from data to real numbers, ranking the data can be solved by ranking the real numbers.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] This mapping is called utility function.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] For label ranking the mapping is a function $f:X\times Y\rightarrow \mathbb {R} \,\!$ such that $y_{i}\succ _{x}y_{j}\Rightarrow f(x,y_{i})>f(x,y_{j})\,\!$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] For instance ranking and object ranking, the mapping is a function $f:X\rightarrow \mathbb {R} \,\!$ .
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Finding the utility function is a regression learning problem which is well developed in machine learning.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] The binary representation of preference information is called preference relation.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] For each pair of alternatives (instances or labels), a binary predicate can be learned by conventional supervised learning approach.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Fürnkranz and Hüllermeier proposed this approach in label ranking problem.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] For object ranking, there is an early approach by Cohen et al.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Using preference relations to predict the ranking will not be so intuitive.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Since observed preference relations may not always be transitive due to inconsistencies in the data, finding a ranking that satisfies all the preference relations may not be possible or may result in multiple possible solutions.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] A more common approach is to find a ranking solution which is maximally consistent with the preference relations.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] This approach is a natural extension of pairwise classification.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Preference learning can be used in ranking search results according to feedback of user preference.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Given a query and a set of documents, a learning model is used to find the ranking of documents corresponding to the relevance with this query.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] More discussions on research in this field can be found in Tie-Yan Liu's survey paper.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Another application of preference learning is recommender systems.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Online store may analyze customer's purchase record to learn a preference model and then recommend similar products to customers.
[src:dpo-alignment/preference-learning] Internet content providers can make use of user's ratings to provide more user preferred contents.
